A reminder:
USDA recently announced free meals to all children until the funding runs out OR December 31, 2020, whichever comes first. This means ALL students attending Northern Tioga School District schools in person can get a free breakfast and a free lunch each day they are at school. Keep in mind this will be until funding runs out OR December 31, 2020 whichever comes first. At which point your child will go back to whatever status they were prior to this time.

We also ask that you look for a survey coming out soon that will ask some questions about preschool aged children and students learning from home.

Any questions can be directed to Judy Quick, Food Service Director judith.quick@ntiogasd.org or 814-258-5644 ext. 1024.

post_text:
A message from our superintendent, Dr. Barnes:

Yesterday, June 3, 2020, the Pennsylvania Department of Education released guidelines for the reopening of Pennsylvania school districts as of July 1, 2020. Under the guidelines, each school district must develop a Health and Safety Plan that is to be approved by the local school board and, upon approval, be submitted to PDE before school districts will be able to open.
The Northern Tioga School District will work on the plan using the guidelines and will also incorporate further guidance that is scheduled to be released mid-June.
We will be asking for input from our community as the plan is developed. Thank you for your patience and understanding as we meet this next challenge of COVID-19.

A Census reminder:

In our country, everyone counts—no matter who you are, what you do, how you worship, or whom you love.

Why do I support the 2020 Census? The census informs where federal funds go every year for things like our healthcare workers, EMTs and firefighters.

No matter where you call home, the 2020 Census is your chance to shape the future of your community. Complete the census today!

Complete the 2020 Census to help shape the next 10 years for health care and infrastructure. There’s still time to respond!

The 2020 Census helps direct billions of dollars of funding for things that your community needs, including roads.

Help the schools in our communities when their doors reopen and for the next 10 years by responding to the 2020 Census now. You can answer online, by phone, or by mail.

The 2020 Census informs funding for the services that keep your community safe and prepared. Complete the census today!

Your answers to the 2020 Census are safe, secure, and used only to produce statistics.

Repond now at:
https://2020census.gov

The Department of Education (PDE) announced today that all schools in the commonwealth will remain closed through at least April 6 as a result of the COVID-19 response efforts. The closure order could be extended beyond April 6 if necessary to save lives and stop the spread of COVID-19.

Under the new timeline, school buildings would reopen on April 7 for two days to allow school administrators, teachers, and other staff time to prepare classrooms, set up cafeterias, schedule transportation and arrange other business operations. Students would return to school on April 9, unless extending the closure is needed in response to the situation with the virus at that time

Please spread the word:

A complete and accurate count is critical for you and your community, because the results of the 2020 Census will affect community funding, congressional representation, and more. Once you receive your invitation you can respond online, by phone or mail.

The census provides critical data that lawmakers, business owners, teachers, and many others use to provide daily services, products, and support for you and your community. Every year, billions of dollars in federal funding go to schools, hospitals, fire departments, roads, and other resources based on census data.

The results of the census also determine the number of seats each state will have in the U.S. House of Representatives, and they are used to draw congressional and state legislative districts.

Participating in the census is required by law, even if you recently completed another survey from the Census Bureau. https://2020census.gov/

Summer Feeding program

With summer here and kids out of school, it’s time to think about keeping children eating healthy while school is out. Each year, the U.S. Department of Agriculture partners with local organizations like schools, community centers and churches to provide free meals to children when school is out for the summer.
Any Child age 18 and under may come and eat for free.

Visit our website for locations, dates and times!

https://www.ntiogasd.org/kids-eat-free-this-summer-2/

Reminder! Clark Wood will be taking promotion pictures for grades Pre K, Kindergarten, and 6th on Wednesday, April 3rd.

Tips for parents:
1. Pony tails and grad caps do not mix.
2. Wear a shirt/dress that will look nice under the gown.
3. Cap and gown color choices are black, pink (prek and k only), or navy (6th grade only).
4. Pictures will be taken in the AM, hopefully before the ketchup hits their shirts.
5. This is a one shot deal. If your student is absent, there will not be make ups.
6. No money is due at the time of pictures. Inter-State Portraits will send you a proof sheet to order from if you wish.
